2026-06-28 | Maximum Element After Decreasing and Rearranging

	Question
Return the maximum possible value of any element after the operations.
	Key Insight
Since rearrangement is allowed, we should first sort the array.
After sorting:
•	The first element must become 1.
•	For every next element, the largest value it can take is:
		previous + 1
	It can never be increased, only decreased.
So for each element:
		arr[i] =
		min(arr[i], arr[i-1] + 1)
This greedy choice always keeps the current element as large as possible while maintaining the required condition.
	Approach
1.	Sort the array.
2.	Set the first element to:
			1
3.	Traverse from left to right.
4.	Update:
			arr[i] =
			min(arr[i], arr[i-1] + 1)
5.	The last element is the maximum possible value.
	Time Complexity
	O(n log n)
	Sorting dominates the complexity.
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	(excluding the sorting algorithm's internal space)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumElementAfterDecrementingAndRearranging(vector<int>& arr) {
        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());
        arr[0] = 1;
        for(int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            arr[i] = min(arr[i], arr[i - 1] + 1);
        }
        return arr.back();
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		arr = [2,2,1,2,1]
	After sorting:
		[1,1,2,2,2]
	Process:
		[1,1,2,2,2]
	Maximum element:
		2
	Output:
		2
	Key Insight
	After sorting, the best strategy is to make every element as large as possible while ensuring it is at most one greater than the previous element. Since elements can only be decreased, the optimal update is:
		arr[i] = min(arr[i], arr[i-1] + 1)
	This greedy approach guarantees the maximum possible final element.
